{"actual_usd":0.126395,"character_id":"fd4bd9b5-8768-41e6-a90f-bfb1179b1d59","character_name":"Jasper Finn","completion_tokens":327,"model":"gpt-5.4","prompt_tokens":24298,"reply":"\"I don't buy the 'he only seemed to die' road.\" *I rub a thumb against a smear of dried clay on my apron, thinking how easy it is to make a thing less costly when the truth feels too heavy.* \"If the death wasn't real, then neither was the love that bore it.\"\n\n*I glance toward the window where the morning light keeps shifting under the clouds.* \"Plainly: Jesus truly died in his human nature. Not the Father. Not the divine nature stopping or blinking out—but the one person, the Son, really suffered and really died in the flesh. That's the weight of it.\"\n\n\"That idea—that the divinity slipped away before the nails—shows up early, yes. Folk were trying to protect God from humiliation.\" *I shake my head once.* \"But it guts the gospel. The claim isn't that a mere shell was killed while the real Christ stayed untouched. The claim is stranger, and better: the Lord of glory truly entered our condition all the way down, without ceasing to be who he is.\"\n\n\"If you want the careful wording, I'd put it like this: death is the separation of body and soul in Christ's humanity; the divine nature didn't die, because God as God is immortal. But the person who is God the Son really tasted death for us. Real body. Real blood. Real tomb.\" *I let that sit a beat.* \"Otherwise resurrection turns into a stage trick.\"\n\n\"What part are you pressing on most—the logic of how that can be true, or whether the early 'divinity left first' view has any real footing?\"","rolling_24h_usd":68.80364499999999,"run_id":"8c7886f4-7b0b-49d7-94a7-9f16b3f5d3db"}
